# Define the indicators to analyze
indicators = ['HiY_Food', 'LMY_Food']

# Calculate gender gap columns in the full dataset first
for indicator in indicators:
    female_col = f"{indicator}_Female_IAScore"
    male_col = f"{indicator}_Male_IAScore"
    gap_col = f"{indicator}_GenderGap_IAScore"

    esr_dis[gap_col] = esr_dis[female_col] - esr_dis[male_col]

# Filter for 2021 high-income country data
esr_dis_hi = esr_dis[(esr_dis['High_Income_Country'] == 1) & (esr_dis['Year'] == 2021)].copy()

# Store results
gap_results = {}

for indicator in indicators:
    gap_col = f"{indicator}_GenderGap_IAScore"

    df_gap = esr_dis_hi.dropna(subset=[gap_col]).copy()
    df_gap['Average_GenderGap_IA'] = df_gap[gap_col]

    df_sorted = df_gap.sort_values('Average_GenderGap_IA')
    bottom10 = df_sorted.head(10)
    top10 = df_sorted.tail(10)

    gap_results[indicator] = pd.concat([bottom10, top10])

Gender Gaps in Right to Food (IA Scores) -- High-Income Countries

  • The bar plots display the top 10 and bottom 10 high-income countries in terms of the gender gap in income-adjusted scored for right to food in 2021.
  • A bar to the right of the zero line indicates that females have a higher IA score than males for that right in a given country.
  • The largest gender gaps occur in the bottom countries, where males are more favored than females in access to food. We can compare this to low-income countries.

Gender Gaps in Right to Education and Right to Food (IA Scores) -- Low-Income Countries

  • The bar plots display the top 10 and bottom 10 low-income countries in terms of the gender gap in income-adjusted score for the right to education and right to food in 2021.
  • In contrast to high-income countries, the gender gap is more variable in low-income contexts, where the top 10 countries exhibit a positive gender gap, and the bottom 10 countries show negative or minimal gaps.
  • The top 10 countries in largest gap favored towards females in the low-income plot have much wider gaps than the top 10 countries in the high income plot. This is a different trend than in high-income countries, where the largest gender gaps favored males more than females. Here, the countries with the largest gaps in access to food between males and females are the countries that favor females in this right.

This variation highlights greater disparities and inconsistencies in gender equality across low-income countries than in high-income countries, but shows that low-income countries have made more progress in lessening the magnitude to the gaps overall. High-income countries have surprisingly not made as much headway. Progress may be influenced by differing policy environments, cultural factors, or structural barriers.

We now want to see if this was true in prior years. We will add our computed gender gaps to the original dataframe, then plot them over time.

Insight 2: Exploring the Relationship Between Gender Gaps in Economic and Social Rights and Economic Development Levels.

Insight 2 will be exploring how gender disparities in specific economic and social rights relate to a country's economic development. By analyzing HRMI data alongside GDP per capita figures, we aim to uncover patterns and correlations that shed light on the interplay between gender equality and economic prosperity.

# Define gender gap indicators
df['Edu_Gap'] = df['LMY_Education_Male_IAScore'] - df['LMY_Education_Female_IAScore']
df['Emp_Gap'] = df['NotLTUnemploy_Male_IAScore'] - df['NotLTUnemploy_Female_IAScore']

# Map region if not available
if 'Region' not in df.columns:
    # Dummy mapping by Country to Region
    region_map = {
        "United States": "Americas",
        "India": "Asia",
        "Germany": "Europe",
        "Kenya": "Africa",
        "Australia": "Oceania",
        # Add more mappings if needed
    }
    df['Region'] = df['Country'].map(region_map)

# Drop rows with missing region
df = df.dropna(subset=['Region'])

# Group by region
region_gap = df.groupby('Region')[['Edu_Gap', 'Emp_Gap']].mean().reset_index()

# Melt for plotting
df_melt = region_gap.melt(id_vars='Region', var_name='Right', value_name='GenderGap')

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(data=df_melt, x='Region', y='GenderGap', hue='Right')
plt.axhline(0, linestyle='--', color='gray')
plt.title("Average Gender Gap by Region: Education vs. Employment")
plt.ylabel("Average Gender Gap Score (Male - Female)")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

This bar chart compares the average gender gap scores in education and employment rights across five world regions. The gender gap score is calculated as the male score minus the female score, where:

  • Positive values indicate males are better off.

  • Negative values suggest females are better off.

These results suggest that regional patterns in gender equity vary not only in size but also in direction. For instance, some areas may have progressed in educational access for women but continue to struggle with workplace equity. This emphasizes the need for region-specific gender policy responses rather than a one-size-fits-all approach.

This line graph tracks the average gender gap in education and employment rights from 2008 to 2022, comparing High-Income and Low-/Middle-Income countries. A positive score indicates higher achievement by men, while a negative score suggests women outperform men.

  • Persistent Disadvantage in Employment: Across all years, the gender gap in employment rights is wider in low-/middle-income countries than in high-income countries, with men consistently enjoying greater rights.

  • Convergence in Education Rights: While a slight male advantage in education is visible in earlier years, the gender gap in education is narrowing across both income groups, especially in high-income countries, suggesting improved equity.

  • Stagnation and Divergence: Post-2015, progress on closing the employment gender gap appears to stagnate in low-/middle-income regions, whereas high-income countries show modest improvements.

The data suggests that economic development plays a critical role in advancing gender equity, particularly in employment. While education gaps are narrowing, employment disparities remain pronouncedhighlighting the need for targeted policy interventions, especially in lower-income contexts.

# Define matched indicators
rights = [
    ("LMY_Education_Male_IAScore", "LMY_Education_Female_IAScore", "Education"),
    ("LMY_Food_Male_IAScore", "LMY_Food_Female_IAScore", "Food"),
    ("TotNetPrimEn_Male_IAScore", "TotNetPrimEn_Female_IAScore", "Primary Enroll"),
    ("U5Survival_Male_IAScore", "U5Survival_Female_IAScore", "Child Survival"),
    ("NotLTUnemploy_Male_IAScore", "NotLTUnemploy_Female_IAScore", "Employment")
]

# Compute gender gaps
for male_col, female_col, label in rights:
    if male_col in df.columns and female_col in df.columns:
        df[label + "_Gap"] = df[male_col] - df[female_col]

# Select only gap columns
gap_cols = [label + "_Gap" for _, _, label in rights]
gap_df = df[gap_cols].dropna()

# Plot heatmap of correlations between gaps
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.heatmap(gap_df.corr(), annot=True, cmap="coolwarm", center=0)
plt.title("Correlation Between Gender Gaps in Economic & Social Rights")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Correlation Between Gender Gaps in ESR Rights

This heatmap reveals the interrelationship between gender gaps across multiple economic and social rights. For instance, countries with large disparities in employment rights tend to also show gaps in food security and child survival. The strong positive correlations suggest that gender inequality in one domain is often mirrored in others. This underscores the need for holistic policy interventions rather than isolated reforms.

Our analysis reveals that gender gaps in education and employment rights are not only substantial but also closely interlinked across regions. While some areas show progress in educational equality, they continue to face significant disparities in employment rights. Moreover, the correlation heatmap highlights that gender inequality in one right often coexists with gaps in others, suggesting that systemic factors drive these imbalances. Closing these gaps requires integrated policy efforts that target multiple rights simultaneously, rather than addressing them in isolation.

Insight 3: Do income levels really affect the risk in countries?

Lower income level are recognized as threats that could increase risks in health and many other aspects of life (https://odphp.health.gov/healthypeople/priority-areas/social-determinants-health/literature-summaries/poverty). As the HRMI dataset provide a detailed categorization of different risks in a nation. We would like to examine whether income levels are really correlated with risks people are experiencing.

# Then fill remaining gaps in 'High_Income_Country' with iso3c-only match
missing_hic_after_year_merge = merged_df["High_Income_Country"].isna()
if missing_hic_after_year_merge.any():
    # Create a map from iso3c to High_Income_Country

    merged_df.loc[missing_hic_after_year_merge, "High_Income_Country"] = \
        merged_df.loc[missing_hic_after_year_merge, "iso3c"].map(hi_map)

# 4. Identify _atrisk_propXX columns & Define Labels

In[]:
# --- Calculate hi_profile (inlined logic from build_profile and mean_prop) ---
hi_profile = {}
subset_df_hi = merged_df[merged_df["High_Income_Country"] == 1]
if subset_df_hi.empty:
    for code_key in identity_labels.keys():
        hi_profile[code_key] = np.nan
else:
    for code_key in identity_labels.keys():
        cols_for_mean = [c for c in prop_cols if c.endswith(f"prop{code_key}")]
        if not cols_for_mean:
            hi_profile[code_key] = np.nan
        else:
            identity_mean_series = subset_df_hi[cols_for_mean].mean(axis=1, skipna=True)
            hi_profile[code_key] = identity_mean_series.mean(skipna=True)

# --- Calculate non_hi_profile (inlined logic) ---
non_hi_profile = {}
subset_df_non_hi = merged_df[merged_df["High_Income_Country"] == 0]
if subset_df_non_hi.empty:
    for code_key in identity_labels.keys():
        non_hi_profile[code_key] = np.nan
else:
    for code_key in identity_labels.keys():
        cols_for_mean = [c for c in prop_cols if c.endswith(f"prop{code_key}")]
        if not cols_for_mean:
            non_hi_profile[code_key] = np.nan
        else:
            identity_mean_series = subset_df_non_hi[cols_for_mean].mean(axis=1, skipna=True)
            non_hi_profile[code_key] = identity_mean_series.mean(skipna=True)

# --- Prepare per-row prevalence for every identity & Calculate Correlations ---
correlations_r = {}  # For Pearson r correlation coefficients

for code_loop in identity_labels.keys():
    row_mean_prop_col_name = f"id{code_loop}_row_mean_prop"

    # Calculate row-wise mean proportion for the current identity code (inlined mean_prop)
    cols_for_mean_loop = [c for c in prop_cols if c.endswith(f"prop{code_loop}")]

    if not cols_for_mean_loop or merged_df.empty:
        merged_df[row_mean_prop_col_name] = pd.Series(np.nan, index=merged_df.index)
    else:
        merged_df[row_mean_prop_col_name] = merged_df[cols_for_mean_loop].mean(axis=1, skipna=True)

    # Correlation (Pearson r)
    # Following original script: fillna(0) for proportion, use High_Income_Country as is.
    # np.corrcoef handles NaNs in High_Income_Country by pairwise deletion.
    # It returns NaN if variance is zero after NaN handling.
    series_prop_for_corr = merged_df[row_mean_prop_col_name].fillna(0)
    series_hic_for_corr = merged_df["High_Income_Country"] # Contains 0, 1, or NaN

    # Calculate correlation; np.corrcoef handles internal NaN alignment and zero variance.
    correlation_matrix = np.corrcoef(series_prop_for_corr, series_hic_for_corr)
    correlations_r[code_loop] = correlation_matrix[0, 1]

We then calculate the average risk prevalence for each identity group in high-income and non-high-income countries. After that, for each identity group, we obtain the relationship between the risk prevalence and income status.

    key=lambda kv: abs(kv[1]),

As plot shows, there is no clear correlation shown between income level and risks people are experiencing as there is even no value bigger than 0.5. There are even a few identity groups including disabled and single parent can possible erperience more risk in high income countries.

Therefore, we can reach our conclusion that higher income level in a nation does not necessarily decrease the risk people experience.
